IGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG028982%2F1"><gtr:id>CB664386-112E-4422-AF73-ACAC413CC07A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Social and religious transformations among exiled Sri Lankan Tamils</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G028982/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This one-year postdoctoral fellowship will enable two key outcomes:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>preparation and completion of a book manuscript for publication based on long-term fieldwork conducted in northern Sri Lanka&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>preparation of a major new piece of research to be undertaken in Sri Lanka.&lt;/li>

&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The projected audience for the book will be anthropologists (students and professionals) and social scientists with an interest in cross-cultural health in post-conflict settings, trauma, and resilience. A series of articles based on the above themes is also proposed that will have both an academic and applied readership.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>Planning for new research that will contribute to improved understandings of violence in post-conflict settings will also be an important component of the fellowship. Continued exploration of the significant changes that have taken place in northern Sri Lanka since the end of hostilities will include new collaborations with colleagues in Sri Lanka and elsewhere, if appropriate.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>A secondary aim of the postdoctoral fellowship is to disseminate findings from research already completed: including conferences, workshops and seminars as well as teaching within UCL's anthropology department. Finally, teaching and research will also be conducted as part of a newly formed collaboration between colleagues at UCL and a locally-based NGO in Chennai South India. This is to teach social science theory and methods to local mental health workers and researchers.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-06-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>80064</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/G028982/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>020361E1-B8CA-49FD-9149-27D31D21C7A3</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Anthropology</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>